Time Series Modeling Training

Samuel Gonzalez

December 4, 2017

Not to be distributed

Background

Time Series models are built when data is serially correlated. That is, when the current point has some relationship to the past point, or the past few points. A seasonal correlations my also be observed in time series data.

The next predicted point can be expressed in terms of an estimation of coefficients*lag terms of the time series.

Motivation

Time Series models allow you to forecast the next point or series of points building upon the historical trend of the data. This is useful in retail, social experiments, stocks (sometimes), energy field. In this case we are modeling a forecast of power generation.

Stationareity

Time Series models should ONLY be build on stationary data. This process is demonstrated on this training

ARIMA Models

  • Predictive power from an Auto Regressive Component (AR)
    • Term Observed in the PACF
  • Predictive power from a Moving Average Component (MA)
    • Term Observed in the ACF
  • Integration Term
    • Differencing the data to achieve stationareity

Validation

  • All models used should be valid
    • Box-LJung Test
    • White Noise Test
  • Parsimony
    • It is preferrable that all estimates are significant
  • Invertibility
    • Does not invalidate the model but care should be taken
summary(df$Power)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   23605   25207   25324   25210   25471   25481
# Create a TimeSeries object

power_ts = ts(df$Power)
# Constant Variance Violated. Implies non-stationariety

plot(power_ts)

# The ACF for the Raw signal shows seasonality. Supports non-stationariety

acf(power_ts, lag.max = 72,xaxp=c(0,72,12))

# The PACF is 'hard to interpret'

pacf(power_ts, lag.max = 72,xaxp=c(0,72,12))

Evidence shows data is not stationary. Take difference of the raw data

power_ts_diff = diff(power_ts, differences = 1)
plot(power_ts_diff)

# The ACF for the differenced raw data still shows seasonality. Supports non-stationariety

acf(power_ts_diff, lag.max = 72,xaxp=c(0,72,24))

# The PACF for the differenced raw data is 'hard to interpret'

pacf(power_ts_diff, lag.max = 72,xaxp=c(0,72,24))

Some Seasonality still observed. Data is still not stationary. Take Seasonal Difference

power_ts_diff_sdiff = diff(power_ts_diff, differences = 1,24)

# Before
plot(power_ts_diff)

# After
plot(power_ts_diff_sdiff)

# Seasonal difference of first order seems to achieve stationariety. ACF Observations here

acf(power_ts_diff_sdiff, lag.max = 24,xaxp=c(0,24,24))

# Seasonal difference of first order seems to achieve stationariety. PACF Observations here

pacf(power_ts_diff_sdiff, lag.max = 96,xaxp=c(0,96,24))

The ACF and PACF functions suggest the following model combinations:

  • Non-Seasonal Part:
    • AR1 through AR14
    • MA1
  • Seasonal Part:
    • AR1 through AR4
    • MA1

It is important to note that only valid models were considered. Out of the list of valid models, the best model was chosen based on an SBC criteria

Once a valid model is chosen the p-values of the estimates can provide further model assessment (parsimony)

The model chosen was:

ARIMA(5,1,1)(0,1,1)24 based on Lowest SBC model that is valid

## Warning: package 'forecast' was built under R version 3.4.3
## Warning: package 'lmtest' was built under R version 3.4.3
## Loading required package: zoo
## Warning: package 'zoo' was built under R version 3.4.3

## 
##     as.Date, as.Date.numeric
power_ts_arima <- arima(power_ts, order=c(5,1,1), seasonal = list(order = c(0,1,1), period = 24)) # fit an ARIMA(5,1,1)(0,1,1)24 model

Before we forecast we make sure the model is valid

power_ts_arima_forecasts <- forecast(power_ts_arima, h=6) #where h is the number of data points to forecast

Box.test(power_ts_arima_forecasts$residuals, lag=72, type="Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  power_ts_arima_forecasts$residuals
## X-squared = 75.069, df = 72, p-value = 0.3792

Box-Ljung test shows lowest p-value > 0.05, so the lags for each of the residual are not statistically significant

plot(power_ts_arima_forecasts$residuals, type = "p")            # make time plot of forecast errors

Residulas are consistent with white noise. Model is Valid

Next, Look at forecast from the valid model

plot(power_ts_arima_forecasts)

# Calculate p-values to see if model is parsimonious

coeftest(power_ts_arima)
## 
## z test of coefficients:
## 
##       Estimate Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)    
## ar1   0.654674   0.049473  13.2330 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ar2   0.164761   0.057206   2.8802  0.003975 ** 
## ar3  -0.032989   0.057700  -0.5717  0.567500    
## ar4   0.040201   0.057365   0.7008  0.483431    
## ar5  -0.155991   0.048876  -3.1916  0.001415 ** 
## ma1  -0.978898   0.014692 -66.6269 < 2.2e-16 ***
## sma1 -0.790193   0.037322 -21.1722 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The model is not parsimonious, not all estimates are significant. The model can be improved upon. We will create a gap model using the fixed option

power_ts_arima_gap <- arima(power_ts, order=c(5,1,1), seasonal = list(order = c(0,1,1), period = 24), fixed = c(NA, NA, 0, 0, NA, NA, NA), transform.pars = F)

We need to investigate if the gap model is valid

power_ts_arima_gap_forecasts <- forecast(power_ts_arima_gap, h=6) #where h is the number of data points to forecast
## Warning in predict.Arima(object, n.ahead = h): MA part of model is not
## invertible
Box.test(power_ts_arima_gap_forecasts$residuals, lag=72, type="Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  power_ts_arima_gap_forecasts$residuals
## X-squared = 76.903, df = 72, p-value = 0.3246

Box-Ljung Test of white noise is passes

Notice the warning about invertibility. This is because of the coefficient of Seasonal MA1 being is -1.022 (abs value > 1). This is not ideal, but will not invalidate your model. Other ARIMA models which are invertible could be investigated. We will stick with the non-parsimonious model

Check the white noise plot

plot(power_ts_arima_gap_forecasts$residuals, type = "p")            # make time plot of forecast errors

The MA1 term has a coefficient of -1.022, which makes the model invertible, as seen below

# Calculate p-values to see if new model is parsimonious

coeftest(power_ts_arima_gap)
## 
## z test of coefficients:
## 
##       Estimate Std. Error  z value  Pr(>|z|)    
## ar1   0.650728   0.049047  13.2674 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ar2   0.161583   0.050049   3.2285  0.001244 ** 
## ar5  -0.143532   0.037474  -3.8302  0.000128 ***
## ma1  -1.021782   0.015392 -66.3827 < 2.2e-16 ***
## sma1 -0.790829   0.037094 -21.3196 < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Though Invertible, the model is now parsimonious

Validation

Compare against a hold out set

Due to the invertibility of the gap model developed, we will carry out predictions on the hold out set using the non-gap model. Then we will discuss further methods to improve the model.

numterms = 12 # Number of terms to hold out and to forecast

df_short = as.data.frame(df[(1:(dim(df)[1]-numterms)),]) # Subset everything but the last 12 terms and use that to build the model

colnames(df_short) <- c("Power")


power_ts_h_out = ts(df_short$Power) # Create a time object for the dataframe subset

power_ts_arima_h_out <- arima(power_ts_h_out, order=c(5,1,1), seasonal = list(order = c(0,1,1), period = 24))

power_ts_arima_forecasts_h_out <- forecast(power_ts_arima_h_out, h=numterms)

forecastedset = as.data.frame(c(power_ts_h_out,power_ts_arima_forecasts_h_out$mean), col.names = c('Forecast'))

forecastedset$idx = seq(1,453,1)

power_ts_raw = ts(df$Power)

mydfstack2 = data.frame(power_ts_raw, forecastedset)

colnames(mydfstack2) = c('actual','predicted','idx')

mydfstack2$idx = seq(1,453,1)

subset = mydfstack2[350:453,]

ggplot(subset, aes(idx)) +
  geom_line(aes(y=actual), colour="red") +
  geom_line(aes(y=predicted), colour="blue")
